Background:		When John was just a boy, he contracted a virus that has come to be known as Lazarus. Only in its infancy in those days, the virus brought him back from the brink of death. It was curable, thanks to the efforts of the finest doctors his family\'92s money could buy, but highly contagious. The virus spread, and it adapted.\uc0\u8232 \u8232 As John grew older, he came to forget his bout with illness. He assumed the virus had been vanquished, though his father founded the Agency in order to fight it. It had not been vanquished; it had only grown stronger. So while John worked as a journalist for his father\'92s company, Grimmer & Sons, he had no idea that the business was a front for the real Agency. It was not until his father\'92s death that he was recruited, by his mother, to run the Agency, under the pseudonym Mr. O, a name which once belonged to his father.\
\
Internal Conflicts:		Mr. O harbours that incredible secret: the world is plagued by the living dead, and no one must know but those Agents of The Agency. He also knows that the Lazarus Virus began with him. With that in mind, he blames himself for the Virus\'92s every victim. He often seems to have a death wish, throwing himself into danger with no regard for his own safety, perhaps to redeem himself for his perceived guilt in bringing the virus to life.\uc0\u8232 \u8232 He is also in love with Miss Monday, but believes it would be wrong to make her fall in love with him; so many of his loved ones have died, he has a lingering fear of loving anyone.\
\
External Conflicts:		Mr. O must battle the living dead.\
